      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That sounds like a classic case of \"goblin\" behavior in your system, where the chaos is hidden behind the scenes. Even after fixing the obvious bugs, you're seeing sporadic latency spikes and 500 errors that don't always log clearly. This often happens when you have a **goblin** in the middle of your stack that's causing unpredictable delays.\n\nHere are a few reasons why your backend might act so sporadically:\n\n1.  **Goblin-Induced Latency**: Sometimes, a third-party service (like your payment gateway or an external API) might be acting like a **goblin** that's just being difficult. They might have a slow response time that varies wildly, or they might be experiencing their own internal issues that you can't see from your logs. This is why the timeout errors are intermittent; the \"goblin\" isn't always there, but when it is, it causes chaos.\n\n2.  **Resource Contention**: If you have multiple services running on the same infrastructure, they might be competing for resources like CPU, memory, or network bandwidth. This can lead to **goblin-like** behavior where one service gets starved of resources, causing it to slow",
